<DOC><DOCNO> AP880706-0316 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1954EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Trump-Casino     07-06 0278</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Trump-Casino,0288</SECOND><HEAD>Trump Proposes Putting Up $75 Million Of His Own Money For NewCasino</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Developer Donald Trump has proposedputting $75 million of his own money into the Taj Mahal casino andselling $675 million in bonds as part of his plans to buy theproject.   In documents filed Tuesday with the federal Securities andExchange Commission in Washington, Trump also indicated the1,250-room hotel and its 120,000-square-foot casino should becompleted by Dec. 1, 1989.   The total purchase price of the Taj Mahal is $261 million,including acquisition fees, according to the SEC filing. It willcost another $493 million to complete the massive hotel casino.   Trump's planned purchase of the Taj Mahal is the result of adeal with entertainer Merv Griffin, who will buy Trump'scontrolling interest in Resorts International Inc. and take thatcompany private.   When the deal is completed, Trump will own the Taj Mahal, somerelated real estate, two ocean piers and a helicopter airline thatoffers service betwen Atlantic City and New York.   Griffin will own the existing Resorts International HotelCasino, the balance of the company's real estate in Atlantic City,its casino properties in the Bahamas and other corporate assets.   Trump has formed a new partnership to acquire the Taj Mahal _Trump Taj Mahal Associates _ which initially will borrow up to $186million from banks and from Trump himself to finance the purchase.Those borrowings will be repaid once the bonds are sold, accordingto the SEC filing.   Trump attorney Nicholas Ribis said Trump has filed a petitionwith the state Casino Control Commission seeking approval of thefinancing plan.</TEXT></DOC>